{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17508358","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17508358"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T12:03:58+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T12:03:58+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2745"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2745","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2745"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.48,0.45,0.02,0.03,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2745"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107619"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2745","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2745"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2745"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"90058"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"13"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"489"},{"type":"tags","id":"1114"},{"type":"tags","id":"1217"},{"type":"tags","id":"1984"},{"type":"tags","id":"12912"},{"type":"tags","id":"12919"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"3588"},{"type":"contributions","id":"3589"},{"type":"contributions","id":"3590"},{"type":"contributions","id":"38424"},{"type":"contributions","id":"38426"},{"type":"contributions","id":"39177"},{"type":"contributions","id":"39178"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107619","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/107619"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 50-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with a two-day history of right-sided pleuritic chest pain. She is seven days post-operative following surgery for adhesive small bowel obstruction. Her medical history includes a deep vein thrombosis (DVT) at age 30 during pregnancy. She does not take any regular medications. She is a non-smoker and does not drink alcohol.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well. Her pulse rate is 105/min, blood pressure 128/78 mmHg, respiratory rate 18/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 36.9\u00b0C. Her right leg is swollen and tender. Chest examination is unremarkable.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EInvestigations reveal an occlusive thrombus in the right common femoral vein on lower limb ultrasound. Screening blood tests show normal renal function. Computed tomography pulmonary angiography has been arranged but not yet performed.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate immediate treatment?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Enoxaparin","Apixaban","Aspirin","Warfarin","Dabigatran"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient has a confirmed proximal DVT, with clinical suspicion for PE. Immediate anticoagulation is indicated to reduce the risk of clot propagation and embolisation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EApixaban\u003C/strong\u003E is a direct oral anticoagulant (DOAC) that can be initiated immediately for the treatment of venous thromboembolism (VTE). It does not require initial parenteral anticoagulation, making it a convenient and effective treatment option for most patients with VTE. Rivaroxaban is similar in this regard. Both are preferred in the absence of contraindications such as severe renal impairment or pregnancy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEnoxaparin\u003C/strong\u003E is a low-molecular-weight heparin (LMWH) administered by subcutaneous injection. It is effective and often used in pregnancy or when oral anticoagulants are contraindicated. However, for most VTEs, DOACs are preferred due to ease of use and similar efficacy and safety.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAspirin\u003C/strong\u003E is not an appropriate treatment for acute VTE. It is much less effective than anticoagulants for preventing recurrence and is not recommended as monotherapy for this indication.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EWarfarin\u003C/strong\u003E is a vitamin K antagonist that requires regular international normalised ratio monitoring and has numerous drug and dietary interactions. It is most commonly used for people with contraindications to DOACs nowadays, such as those with mechanical heart valves, severe renal impairment, or antiphospholipid syndrome.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDabigatran\u003C/strong\u003E is a DOAC, but unlike apixaban and rivaroxaban, it requires at least five days of initial parenteral anticoagulation before it can be commenced for VTE. Hence, it is not the preferred option.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EComparison of anticoagulants:\u003Cbr /\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cdiv class=\u0022table-container\u0022\u003E\u003Ctable\u003E\u003Ctbody\u003E\u003Ctr\u003E\u003Cth colspan=\u00221\u0022 rowspan=\u00221\u0022\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAnticoagulant\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/th\u003E\u003Cth colspan=\u00221\u0022 rowspan=\u00221\u0022\u003E\u003Cp\u003EMechanism\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/th\u003E\u003Cth colspan=\u00221\u0022 rowspan=\u00221\u0022\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAdministration\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/th\u003E\u003Cth colspan=\u00221\u0022 rowspan=\u00221\u0022\u003E\u003Cp\u003EMonitoring\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/th\u003E\u003Cth colspan=\u00221\u0022 rowspan=\u00221\u0022\u003E\u003Cp\u003EKey Contraindications\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/th\u003E\u003Cth colspan=\u00221\u0022 rowspan=\u00221\u0022\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECommon Indications\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/th\u003E\u003C/tr\u003E\u003Ctr\u003E\u003Ctd colspan=\u00221\u0022 rowspan=\u00221\u0022\u003E\u003Cp\u003EApixaban/Rivaroxaban\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/td\u003E\u003Ctd colspan=\u00221\u0022 rowspan=\u00221\u0022\u003E\u003Cp\u003EDirect factor Xa inhibitors\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/td\u003E\u003Ctd colspan=\u00221\u0022 rowspan=\u00221\u0022\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOral\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/td\u003E\u003Ctd colspan=\u00221\u0022 rowspan=\u00221\u0022\u003E\u003Cp\u003ENone routine\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/td\u003E\u003Ctd colspan=\u00221\u0022 rowspan=\u00221\u0022\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESevere renal impairment, pregnancy, mechanical heart valves\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/td\u003E\u003Ctd colspan=\u00221\u0022 rowspan=\u00221\u0022\u003E\u003Cp\u003EVTE, atrial fibrillation, post-orthopaedic surgery prophylaxis\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/td\u003E\u003C/tr\u003E\u003Ctr\u003E\u003Ctd colspan=\u00221\u0022 rowspan=\u00221\u0022\u003E\u003Cp\u003EDabigatran\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/td\u003E\u003Ctd colspan=\u00221\u0022 rowspan=\u00221\u0022\u003E\u003Cp\u003EDirect thrombin inhibitor\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/td\u003E\u003Ctd colspan=\u00221\u0022 rowspan=\u00221\u0022\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOral\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/td\u003E\u003Ctd colspan=\u00221\u0022 rowspan=\u00221\u0022\u003E\u003Cp\u003ENone routine\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/td\u003E\u003Ctd colspan=\u00221\u0022 rowspan=\u00221\u0022\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESevere renal impairment, pregnancy, mechanical heart valves\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/td\u003E\u003Ctd colspan=\u00221\u0022 rowspan=\u00221\u0022\u003E\u003Cp\u003EVTE (after initial parenteral therapy), atrial fibrillation\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/td\u003E\u003C/tr\u003E\u003Ctr\u003E\u003Ctd colspan=\u00221\u0022 rowspan=\u00221\u0022\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWarfarin\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/td\u003E\u003Ctd colspan=\u00221\u0022 rowspan=\u00221\u0022\u003E\u003Cp\u003EVitamin K antagonist\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/td\u003E\u003Ctd colspan=\u00221\u0022 rowspan=\u00221\u0022\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOral\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/td\u003E\u003Ctd colspan=\u00221\u0022 rowspan=\u00221\u0022\u003E\u003Cp\u003ERegular INR\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/td\u003E\u003Ctd colspan=\u00221\u0022 rowspan=\u00221\u0022\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPregnancy\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/td\u003E\u003Ctd colspan=\u00221\u0022 rowspan=\u00221\u0022\u003E\u003Cp\u003EMechanical heart valves, antiphospholipid syndrome, VTE in severe renal impairment\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/td\u003E\u003C/tr\u003E\u003Ctr\u003E\u003Ctd colspan=\u00221\u0022 rowspan=\u00221\u0022\u003E\u003Cp\u003EEnoxaparin\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/td\u003E\u003Ctd colspan=\u00221\u0022 rowspan=\u00221\u0022\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIndirect factor Xa inhibitor\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/td\u003E\u003Ctd colspan=\u00221\u0022 rowspan=\u00221\u0022\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESubcutaneous\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/td\u003E\u003Ctd colspan=\u00221\u0022 rowspan=\u00221\u0022\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAnti-Xa levels in specific cases\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/td\u003E\u003Ctd colspan=\u00221\u0022 rowspan=\u00221\u0022\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHeparin-induced thrombocytopenia, severe renal impairment\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/td\u003E\u003Ctd colspan=\u00221\u0022 rowspan=\u00221\u0022\u003E\u003Cp\u003EVTE in pregnancy, initial treatment before warfarin/dabigatran, perioperative bridging\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/td\u003E\u003C/tr\u003E\u003C/tbody\u003E\u003C/table\u003E\u003C/div\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Direct oral anticoagulants (DOACs) are first-line therapy for most cases of VTE.","Apixaban and rivaroxaban can be initiated without prior parenteral anticoagulation, unlike dabigatran.","Low-molecular-weight heparin (LMWH) and vitamin K antagonists are reserved for specific indications or contraindications to DOACs."],"references":["Kearon C, Akl EA, Ornelas J, Blaivas A, Jimenez D, Bounameaux H, et al. Antithrombotic Therapy for VTE Disease: CHEST Guideline and Expert Panel Report. Chest. 2016;149(2):315-52. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/26867832/","Tran HA, Gibbs H, Merriman E, Curnow JL, Young L, Bennett A, et al. New guidelines from the Thrombosis and Haemostasis Society of Australia and New Zealand for the diagnosis and management of venous thromboembolism. Med J Aust. 2019;210(5):227-35. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/30739331/","Agnelli G, Becattini C, Meyer G, Mu\u00f1oz A, Huisman MV, Connors JM, et al. Apixaban for the Treatment of Venous Thromboembolism Associated with Cancer. N Engl J Med. 2020;382(17):1599-607. Available at: https://www.nejm.org/doi/full/10.1056/NEJMoa1915103"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"90058"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2745"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"90058","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/90058"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-07-01T12:04:28+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-07-01T12:26:06+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2745"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107619"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"13","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/13"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\ude78","name":"Haematology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:44+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"76","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/76"},"